{{Infobox organization | name = Terma Foundation | logo = TermaLogo.jpg | type = [[Non-profit organization|Non-profit]] | founded=1993 | location = | fields = Health care | homepage = http://www.terma.org }} The '''Terma Foundation''' was founded in 1993 as the '''Tibet Child Nutrition Project''' ('''TCNP'''), by Dr. [[Nancy S. Harris]] and now implements public health programs including nutrition, education, primary and preventive health care, acknowledging traditional belief systems, and integrating low-tech, low-cost western [[technology]] where appropriate in [[Tibet]].<ref>[http://www.phayul.com/news/article.aspx?id=4438&article=American+Doctor+Honored+for+Health+Projects+in+Tibet&t=1&c=1 American Doctor Honored for Health Projects in Tibet]</ref><ref>Susan Craig, [http://www.terma.org/shambhalasun052004.pdf Saving Tibet's Children] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728090113/http://www.terma.org/shambhalasun052004.pdf |date=2011-07-28 }}, ''Shambhala Sun'', May 2000, pp. 52-56.</ref>
Terma's work in the [[Tibet Autonomous Region]] and adjacent ethnic Tibetan areas of the [[People's Republic of China]] is carried out by a multidisciplinary coalition of [[Tibetans]], [[Chinese people|Chinese]], and [[Westerners]] in successful cooperation with PRC nationals and local health authorities.
Dr. Harris gained notoriety when she published an article in the [[New England Journal of Medicine]] with the results of her study on stunted growth in the [[Himalaya]] region. She measured 2,500 children in rural villages and concluded that malnutrition was the cause rather than altitude, as previously suspected. To aid their work with local communities, the organization conducted a systematic study on the effectiveness of traditional Tibetan medicine in preventing and treating child health problems. They also studied the impact of vitamins and sunlight exposure in preventing rickets.<ref>[https://archive.is/20120723022539/http://www.chinadevelopmentbrief.com/dingo/Province/Tibet/1-43-0-207-0-0.html China Development Brief]</ref> The foundation's field operations, based in Lhasa, now reach an estimated 300,000 child and community beneficiaries each year.<ref>[http://www.worldofchildren.org/honorees/2006-honorees/54-nancy-harris World of Children Award Nominees]{{Dead link|date=June 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}</ref>
The objectives of the foundation include:
• Focusing on the health and welfare of children, women, and the elderly who maintain indigenous values while confronting contemporary challenges;
• Promoting environmentally appropriate traditional agriculture, consumption of high nutrient indigenous foods, and cultivation of Tibetan herbs;
• Supporting educational programs in public health, literacy, vocational training, the arts, and international education exchange;
• Developing microeconomic initiatives at the grassroots level which will sustain the local health infrastructure; and
• Facilitating interaction between Tibetans and other indigenous communities internationally and on issues relating to health, education, and the environment.
