{{EngvarB|date=November 2013}} {{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}} {{Infobox building |name = Vinohrady Water Tower |native_name = Vinohradská vodárna |native_name_lang = cs |image = Vodárenská věž, Praha Vinohrady.JPG |caption = The tower |highest_start = |highest_end = |location = 725 Korunní Street, [[Prague]], Czech Republic |coordinates = {{coord|50.0752|14.4491|display=inline}} |start_date = |completion_date = 1882 |opening = |building_type = Water Tower |antenna_spire = |roof = |top_floor = |floor_count = >7 |elevator_count = |cost = |floor_area = |architect = [[Antonín Turek]] |structural_engineer= |main_contractor = |developer = |owner = [[Prague|City of Prague]], Czech Republic |management = |references = }}
'''Vinohrady Water Tower''' ({{lang-cs|Vinohradská vodárna}}) is a building in [[Vinohrady]] in [[Prague 10]] which was originally built as a water tower. Today its architecture is acknowledged as culturally important although it is now converted to accommodate offices and apartments. The viewing platform at the top is 40 metres above the street level.
==History== The Vinohrady water tower building was created in 1882 to house steam engines and an underground reservoir. The engines pumped water up from the reservoir, creating a gravitational feed to nearby homes and businesses. Antonin Turek designed the building while he was the municipal architect.<ref name=stove>[http://stovezata.praha.eu/en-water-tower-of-vinohrady.html Water Tower of Vinohrady], stovezata.praha.eu, retrieved 14 November 2013</ref>
The seventh floor originally contained a tank that could hold 200 cubic metres of water.<ref name=stove/> Initially this was pumped from the [[River Vltava]] until 1912, when the water source was switched to a plant at [[Káraný]]. The water descended from the tank to supply [[Strašnice]], [[Žižkov]] and [[Vršovice (Prague)|Vršovice]] with drinking water.<ref name=stove/>
In 1914 the tower's steam engines were replaced with electric motors. The revised system used water that was treated at a plant at [[Podolí (Prague)|Podolí]] and then stored in water tanks underground before being pumped to the top of this tower for use.<ref>[http://www.digital-guide.cz/en/poi/vinohrady-2/vinohrady-water-tower/ Vonohrady Water Tower], Prague Minos Guide, retrieved 14 November 2013</ref>
== Architecture == Today its architecture is acknowledged to be of national historical importance, even though the building serves no modern purpose for water supply, as the motors, pumps and pipes have been removed. In 1993, the inside was converted to accommodate offices and apartments.<ref name=desit>[http://desitka.cz/368-vinohradska-vodarna-cerpala-vodu-primo-z-vltavy.html Vinohrady waterworks pump water directly from the river], Desitka.cz, retrieved 17 November 2013</ref> The viewing platform at the top is 40 metres above the street level – once this provided a commanding view of the area, but today it is only slightly taller than the tenements that surround the tower. On each corner there are the statues of angels with clock faces between them. Below the clocks are four medallions celebrating Vinohrady.<ref name=desit>[http://desitka.cz/368-vinohradska-vodarna-cerpala-vodu-primo-z-vltavy.html Vinohrady waterworks pump water directly from the river], Desitka.cz, retrieved 17 November 2013</ref> In 1991 the tower was recognised as being of cultural importance and was listed by the [[Czech Ministry of Culture]].<ref>[http://monumnet.npu.cz/pamfond/list.php?IdReg=159933 Water Tower – ref 47348/1-2151], monumnet.npu.cz, retrieved 17 November 2013</ref>
